    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-05-19T12:46:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-05-19T12:46:00-05:00" n="141"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d141">
                <head>141. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Vietnam</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d141fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> (US) VIET S. Secret; Immediate;
                            <gloss target="#t_Exdis1">Exdis</gloss>. Text received from the White
                        House; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_BDE1">Bell</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BWP1">William Bundy</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNJT1">McNaughton</persName>; and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_ULS1">Unger</persName>. Repeated to <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCPAC1">CINCPAC</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-05-19T13:46:00-04:00">May 19, 1966, 1:46 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3531. For <persName corresp="#p_PWJ1">Porter</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_KRW1">Komer</persName>. Non-military programs reviewed at
                    highest level with Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LHC1">Lodge</persName>
                    present 16 May.<note n="2" xml:id="d141fn2">See <ref target="#d140">Document
                            140</ref>.</note> The following measures were decided upon: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Make urgent three-pronged attack on inflation. <list>
                                <label>a.</label>
                                <item>
                                    <gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                                        >AID</gloss> will each make all-out effort to reduce to
                                    minimum inflationary impact of further US buildup. <gloss
                                        target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> is analyzing possibility of
                                    keeping demands on local economy and manpower at <gloss
                                        target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1966 rate, despite increase in
                                    deployments and construction program—the analysis and a plan for
                                    accomplishing an agreed-upon goal will be completed about 1 June
                                    (breakdown of <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 66 target
                                    ceilings explained in <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 2227,
                                    17 May, para 1a.).<note n="3" xml:id="d141fn3">Not found.</note>
                                </item>
                                <label>b.</label>
                                <item>US will make all-out effort to eliminate bottlenecks to
                                    massive flow of aid commodities, especially port and in-country
                                    transport congestion. US military will assist in providing
                                    shipping, port aid, and in-country lift as required. US will
                                    insist that <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> take essential
                                    steps speed flow of goods, if necessary using leverage of
                                    suspension aid shipments and/or new aid tranches till
                                    bottlenecks removed. <gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> will
                                    make prompt contingency study of US military takeover Saigon
                                    port and deliveries to importers. Instructions are being sent
                                    Embassy and <gloss target="#t_MACV1">MACV</gloss> (<gloss
                                        target="#t_Septel1">septel</gloss>s)<note n="4"
                                        xml:id="d141fn4">Not further identified.</note> for
                                    coordinated mission council recommendations by 31 May.</item>
                                <label>c.</label>
                                <item>As soon as <gloss target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss> recommendations
                                    available, US will present to <gloss target="#t_GVN1"
                                        >GVN</gloss> revised Honolulu package of maximum realizable
                                    fiscal measures designed to sop up at least 10 billion piasters
                                    during the last six months of <gloss target="#t_CY1">CY</gloss>
                                    1966.</item>
                                <label>d.</label>
                                <item>Negotiating strategy will be planned in light of <gloss
                                        target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss> recommendations as reviewed
                                    Saigon and Washington, with appropriate consideration desirable
                                    carrots as well as sticks. Possible carrots might include US
                                    approval of wage increase, US financial support of new <gloss
                                        target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> land reform initiative, and
                                    help in establishment <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                                    <gloss target="#t_PX1">PX</gloss> system if current analyses
                                    establish their feasibility in time. <gloss target="#t_FYI1"
                                        >FYI</gloss>. Though not discussed, US provision of <gloss
                                        target="#t_CIP1">CIP</gloss> security stockpile might be an
                                    added carrot. End <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>. Sticks to
                                    provide leverage might include withholding approval further
                                        <gloss target="#t_CIP1">CIP</gloss> tranches or other means
                                    to be studied promptly.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <pb facs="0427" n="391" xml:id="pg_391"/>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>We will increase annual rate of <gloss target="#t_RD1">RD</gloss>
                            Cadre output from 19,000 to 39,000 as fast as instructors are available
                            to maintain quality. <gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss> will provide
                            construction resources as needed to construct new training center.
                                <persName corresp="#p_KRW1">Komer</persName> will resolve with
                            appropriate agencies issue of how added cost is apportioned.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>We will expedite expansion police forces to 72,000 end <gloss
                                target="#t_CY1">CY</gloss> 1966 goal, and promptly study further
                            expansion of police as the preferred longer term internal security
                            instrument.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Aside from <gloss target="#t_RD1">RD</gloss> Cadres, <gloss
                                target="#t_SecDef1">SecDef</gloss> and <persName corresp="#p_KRW1"
                                >Komer</persName> will defer approval of any <gloss target="#t_FY1"
                                >FY</gloss> 1967 <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> manpower
                            increases until overall agreement is reached on civil/military
                            allocation. This means in effect a temporary freeze on all force
                            ceilings at end <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1966 approved levels
                            until manpower budget can be worked out.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Foregoing <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss> and should be closely
                            held.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
